<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910816-0063</DOCNO><DOCID>910816-0063.</DOCID><HL>   Texfi-Robinson Humphrey Pact</HL><DATE>08/16/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   TXF</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>GEORGIA (GA)NORTH CAROLINA (NC)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   RALEIGH, N.C. -- Texfi Industries Inc. said it enteredinto an agreement with Robinson Humphrey Co., an Atlantainvestment banker, to provide financial services, includingadvice on possible divestitures, raising capital and othercorporate matters.   Michael A. Miller, Texfi's executive vice president andchief financial officer, said the company wants to improveits finished-fabrics operations and &quot;reduce debt and relatedexpenses.&quot; He said possible candidates for divestiture couldinclude the company's T-shirt, unfinished fabrics or its yarnoperations.</LP><TEXT>   Texfi, a textile and apparel manufacturer, also said itexpects to report a loss in its third quarter, primarily dueto discontinued fleece-apparel operations. The company saidit will report third-quarter results about Aug. 28.   In its 1990 third quarter, Texfi reported net income of$1.5 million, or nine cents a share, on revenue of $73.1million.</TEXT></DOC>